  <div class="container"> <h1>Adding a Close Event When the User Closes the Browser in GWT</h1>

<p>Often times your GWT app will queue up client side RPC events. What if
the user clicks close on the browser window or tries to navigate to a
new page? The solution is very simple.</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre><span class="n">Window</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="na">addWindowClosingHandler</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="k">new</span> <span class="n">ClosingHandler</span><span class="o">(){</span>
    <span class="nd">@Override</span> <span class="kd">public</span> <span class="kt">void</span> <span class="n">onWindowClosing</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="n">ClosingEvent</span> <span class="n">event</span><span class="o">)</span> <span class="o">{</span>
        <span class="n">event</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="na">setMessage</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="s">&quot;If you leave, you may lose data. Continue?&quot;</span><span class="o">);</span>
    <span class="o">}</span>
<span class="o">});</span>
</pre></div>

<p>Simple as pie. If event.setMessage is called, a prompt will be displayed
for you.</p>


